DUKE IMPEACHED, SET TO TRIAL FOR MAIL FRAUD

December 14, 1992-Not even one year into his highly unpopular tenure as governor, David Duke has been removed from office as he awaits trial on tax fraud in addition to a slew of other accusations of bigotry. Since his inauguration in January of this year, Duke has failed to pass a single budget bill due to his frequent use of the line item veto to try and cut welfare spending to absurdly low numbers as well as failing to repeal affirmative action. In March, Black legislators led a walkout of the Louisiana state legislature over alleged comments that Duke had used racial slurs to refer to them and called them as much of a waste of space in this legislature as queens to welfare. But this would only be the beginning of Dukes actions finally catching up to him, as multiple government officials reported of Dukes open intent to file a false tax return to fleece his supporters and acquire more money for gambling, the full legalization of which was one of the few bills he signed off on during his tenure. Articles of Impeachment passed 104-1 in the State House and the State Senate agreed on conviction unanimously, largely owing up to voice memos between Dukes chief of staff and the Governor where he talks of slicing a few thousand dollars off here or there to make his situation more believable. As a result of this removal, Lieutenant Governor Melinda Schwegmann, a Democrat, will assume his duties until the 1995 election. At a press conference to announce his removal from the Governorship, Duke was rushed by a man bearing a sign that read Duke: Did Nazi That Money On His Taxes a reference to the case and Dukes past associations with the neo-Nazi movement. Outside of the governors mansion, a sea of Black residents came out to celebrate Dukes removal, with hip hop group MC T Tucker and DJ Irvs rap record Where Dey At? blasting over the proceedings When reporters asked the two men why they had shown up, Tucker responded that We just making sure that motherfucker stays gone.
